<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-967-322  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 967 322.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Dec 11 1989 v8 n25 p85(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM to provide image processing for EPA. (Environmental ProtectionAgency)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, James M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM AS-400 (Minicomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Image ProcessingGovernment ContractsOffice AutomationOptical DisksUnited States. Environmental Protection AgencyInformation Resources Management.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM to Procide Image Processing for EPAandM;Under a $70 million contract awarded last month, IBM Corp. will provide imageprocessing capability to Environmental Protection Agency offices nationwide.andM;Agency officials expect the image processing to save money in 12 programs,including the Superfund Transaction Automated Retrieval System (STARS).andM;They also expect the heavy investment in optical-disk technology to reducethe agency's reliance on paper records significantly.andM;&quot;The potential here is tremendous.andP;  EPA is paper-intensive, and informationexchange is typically done with the transfer of paper,&quot; said Ted Harris,chief of the Architectural Management and Planning Branch of EPA's NationalData Processing Division in Research Triangle, N.C.andP;  &quot;The whole arena oftrying to capture data at the source, and tying it together is thechallenge.&quot;andM;The five-year indefinite-quantity, indefinite-delivery contract includes ahost system, optical disks loaded into a jukebox, scanners, workstations andperipherals.andM;Image processing will allow EPA employees to scan documents and convert themto digitized format, storing the image on high-capacity optical disks.andP;  Querycommands on a relational database management system retrieve the documents.andO;Users can print the data on laser printers.andM;IBM Provides HostsandM;EPA will operate with two host processors.andP;  Both processors are from IBM'sAS/400 family.andP;  The standard Level I host is an AS/400 Model 50 with 16M ofmemory and more than 800M of magnetic-disk storage.andP;  The Level II host is anAS/400 Model 30 with 8M of memory and 800M of magnetic-disk storage.andM;IBM announced it will use an OSAR 64 optical-disk jukebox made by FileNetCorp. of Costa Mesa, Calif., with the Level I host processor.andP;  The jukeboxcontains three optical-disk drivers from Laser Magnetic Storage InternationalCo. of Colorado Springs, Colo.andM;The Level II hosts will use stand-alone disk drives.andM;Harris said the FileNet jukebox has 64 12-inch write once/read-many disks andthe system could expand to 204 disks.andM;Each disk stores 2.3 gigabytes of data, for a total of more than 450gigabytes per jukebox.andM;The workstations are IBM PS/2 Model 80s with 2M of memory and a 19-inch,114-dot-per-inch monochrome monitor.andP;  The workstation contains an adapterthat performs facsimile-type data compression and decompression Workstationsare connected to the host processor by a token-ring local area network.andM;The system runs IBM's AS/400 Electronic Image Filing Cabinet System for imageprocessing.andM;It runs on both the host processor and the workstation, enabling the user toscan, index, store, retrieve and print images, and perform other functions.andM;&quot;With these jukeboxes we can condense down 7 million pages of information or40 to 50 file cabinets worth of information,&quot; Harris said.andM;STARS gives EPA lawyers and Superfund officials faster access to essentialcost recovery documents.andP;  More than 1,200 hazardous waste sites now receiveSuperfund money.andO;</TEXT></DOC>